Wraps the `claude` CLI as a testable trait boundary; the rest of ctx-brief's gather/plan stages depend on `Claude`, not on shelling out directly, so unit tests can substitute a fake implementation.

`ClaudeCli` is the real implementation (default binary name `"claude"`, overridable via `ClaudeCli::new(command: String)`). It always runs with `current_dir(cwd)` set to the target repo, deliberately, so that repo's own `PostToolUse` context hooks fire during the call — moving `cwd` elsewhere silently breaks hook-triggered context loading. Prompts are never inlined in Rust source: `system` is passed via `--append-system-prompt` (appended to Claude's default system prompt, not a replacement), and `user` is the dynamic assembled input.

Two entry points: `print(&self, system: &str, user: &str, model: Option<&str>, allowed_tools: &[String], cwd: &Path) -> Result<String, BriefError>` runs headless (`claude -p`), feeds `user` on stdin, captures stdout via the private `capture` helper, and is used by gather/headless-plan stages. `interactive(&self, system: &str, user: &str, model: Option<&str>, cwd: &Path) -> Result<(), BriefError>` inherits stdio so a human drives the session directly, passes `user` as a positional CLI arg (not stdin) to seed the first turn, and does not capture output — the session itself is expected to write the brief file as a side effect.

Invariants: `print` returns `Err(BriefError::Claude(_))` if the child fails to spawn, exits non-zero, or produces empty/whitespace-only stdout — never returns `Ok("")`. `allowed_tools` empty means no `--allowedTools` flag is passed at all (not an explicit empty allowlist flag). `push_model` is a shared helper appending `--model <m>` only when `Some`.